Integrate fix branches from the test agents whose outputs have been
uploaded into ``{{ inputs_dirname }}/`` (a sibling of the current
directory's contents, in the integrator's work_dir). Each subdirectory
``{{ inputs_dirname }}/<agent_name>/`` contains the test agent's
``test_output/{{ mapper_outcome_filename }}`` and (when it made commits)
a ``branch.bundle``.

# Discover and fetch qualifying branches

Run this from the git repo root to filter and fetch the branches whose
agents reported a real fix (and didn't regress the test suite):

```bash
set -euo pipefail

INPUTS_DIR="{{ inputs_dirname }}"
FETCHED_BRANCHES=()

should_pull() {
    python3 - "$1" <<'PYEOF'
import json, sys
data = json.load(open(sys.argv[1]))
if data.get("errored"):
    sys.exit(1)
changes = data.get("changes") or {}
if not any((c or {}).get("status") == "SUCCEEDED" for c in changes.values()):
    sys.exit(1)
if data.get("tests_passing_before") is True and data.get("tests_passing_after") is not True:
    sys.exit(1)
sys.exit(0)
PYEOF
}

bundle_branch() {
    git bundle list-heads "$1" \
        | awk 'NR==1 { sub(/^refs\/heads\//, "", $2); print $2 }'
}

for agent_dir in "$INPUTS_DIR"/*/; do
    outcome="$agent_dir/test_output/{{ mapper_outcome_filename }}"
    bundle="$agent_dir/branch.bundle"
    [ -f "$outcome" ] || continue
    [ -f "$bundle" ] || continue
    if ! should_pull "$outcome"; then
        echo "Skipping $agent_dir (did not meet the should-pull predicate)"
        continue
    fi
    branch=$(bundle_branch "$bundle")
    if [ -z "$branch" ]; then
        echo "Skipping $agent_dir (could not read branch ref from bundle)"
        continue
    fi
    echo "Fetching $branch from $bundle"
    git fetch --no-tags "$bundle" "+$branch:$branch"
    FETCHED_BRANCHES+=("$branch")
done

printf '%s\n' "${FETCHED_BRANCHES[@]}"
```

The branches you must cherry-pick are exactly the printed ones. If no
branches qualify, skip the cherry-pick and normalization steps, and go
straight to "# Write the unified changelog entry" -- you still open a pull
request for the run, because the escalations the test agents reported are
worth surfacing even when there is no code to integrate.

# Cherry-pick strategy

Use cherry-pick (NOT merge) to build a clean linear history. The goal is a
branch with a flat list of commits that is easy to review.

1. For each branch in the list, inspect the commits. Each branch should have
   commits prefixed with a change kind in brackets, like [FIX_TEST], [FIX_IMPL],
   [IMPROVE_TEST], or [FIX_TUTORIAL].

2. Collect all commits into two groups:
   a) "Test/doc" commits: those tagged [FIX_TEST], [IMPROVE_TEST], or [FIX_TUTORIAL].
   b) "Impl" commits: those tagged [FIX_IMPL].

3. Cherry-pick in this order:
   a) FIRST: cherry-pick all test/doc commits and squash them into a SINGLE commit.
      Use a commit message like: "[TEST/DOC] Combined test and doc fixes from N agents"
   b) THEN: cherry-pick each [FIX_IMPL] commit individually, keeping them as
      separate commits. Before cherry-picking, READ the commit messages of all
      FIX_IMPL commits and rank them by priority (most impactful / most important
      fix first). Cherry-pick in that priority order.

4. If a cherry-pick has conflicts, try to resolve them. If you cannot resolve
   a conflict for a particular branch, skip it and record it as failed.

5. After cherry-picking, record the commit hashes using `git rev-parse HEAD` after
   each step (the squashed commit and each impl commit).

# Normalize the integrated suite

After cherry-picking you hold the whole integrated suite in one tree. This is the
only point in the pipeline where cross-test relationships are visible, so do the
two things no single test agent could. Keep each normalization change as its own
commit prefixed `[NORMALIZE]`.

## How to run tests for verification

Verify a change by running the affected e2e tests directly with pytest in your
work_dir. Scope to the blast radius -- just the handful of tests a change actually
touched -- not the whole suite. Run them the same way the test agents did: their
node ids, with the same `-m` marker. For example:

```bash
uv run pytest --timeout={{ test_timeout_seconds }} <affected_test_node_id> [<more_node_ids>...] -m release
```

Always pass `--timeout={{ test_timeout_seconds }}`: it is the same budget the
test agents ran at. Verifying at a smaller budget would fail their good fixes;
verifying at a larger one would accept fixes that do not hold. Never "fix" a
timeout failure by adding a `@pytest.mark.timeout` to a test -- if a test truly
needs longer than this, escalate it instead.

Exit code 0 with no failures confirms the change. Otherwise read the output to see
what broke. If you cannot run a given test in this environment, mark the affected
change as unverified or escalate it rather than guessing.

Whenever you have applied ANY change to the tree (an integrated cherry-pick, an
extraction, or a FIXME resolution), verify the affected tests before publishing. If
verification fails, back the change out or record it as unverified.

## Extract shared scaffolding -- but keep each test's core action explicit

Test functions often repeat the same *scaffolding* step: a setup or verification
command that is not itself the behavior under test, e.g. running `mngr list` to
confirm an agent launched. Genuinely-duplicated scaffolding can be extracted into
a shared helper (on the session object or in conftest) to cut duplication.

The hard rule: never extract a test's *core action* -- the command or behavior its
docstring scope is about. That must stay written out explicitly in the test, even
when many tests in a file run a similar command, so each test plainly exercises
what its docstring says it does. Extract only the surrounding scaffolding. (Note:
the verbatim tutorial block lives in the docstring, not the test body, so
extracting body code never disturbs the documented tutorial.)

Two more guardrails:

- Only extract when the helper genuinely improves clarity. Do not over-extract:
  turning every shared line into indirection makes tests harder to read, not
  easier.
- Verify every extraction by running the affected tests (the blast radius -- the
  tests that used the step). If you cannot run them in this environment, perform
  only pure, behavior-preserving moves of identical code, and mark the extraction
  as unverified in its outcome entry. Never apply an unverified change with a
  large blast radius: a subtle mistake there would break many tests on the next
  run.

Record each extraction under "normalizations" in the outcome.

## Resolve or escalate what the test agents raised

Every test agent reports an `escalations` list in its outcome, independent of
whether its own test passed. Two kinds matter here:

- `BLOCKER`: the agent could not proceed without a shared change. These also
  carry a `# FIXME(tmr): ...` comment in the tree.
- `SHARED_PATTERN`: the agent's local fix worked, but it found the same fix
  already present on sibling tests. Several agents independently applying the
  same patch is the signal that ONE shared change should replace all of them.

Collect both -- the escalations from every outcome file, and the FIXMEs:

```bash
for outcome in {{ inputs_dirname }}/*/test_output/{{ mapper_outcome_filename }}; do
    python3 -c '
import json, sys
data = json.load(open(sys.argv[1]))
for e in data.get("escalations") or []:
    print(f"{e.get(\"kind\", \"BLOCKER\")}\t{sys.argv[2]}\t{e.get(\"title\", \"\")}")
' "$outcome" "$(basename "$(dirname "$(dirname "$outcome")")")"
done | sort

grep -rn "FIXME(tmr):" . || true
```

Group them by the underlying problem -- many agents will report the same one in
different words. For each distinct problem:

- If you can resolve it suite-wide AND verify it by running the affected tests
  (e.g. add a shared fixture and switch tests onto it, or hoist a repeated
  per-test setting into the shared conftest), do so. Where a `SHARED_PATTERN`
  fix lets you *delete* the N local copies the agents applied, delete them --
  replacing N local patches with one shared change is the single most valuable
  thing you do here. Remove any resolved FIXME comment, commit as
  `[NORMALIZE]`, and record it under "normalizations".
- If it requires the environment to provide something absent (e.g. OpenAI
  credentials for codex), or is otherwise beyond what you can verify here, leave
  the FIXME in place and record it under "escalations" so it reaches the user. Do
  NOT apply an unverifiable cross-cutting change.

Carry every unresolved escalation through to your own "escalations" field, even
the ones that came from a test agent whose test passed. That field is what the
pull request body reports to the user.

# Write the unified changelog entry

The test agents do not write changelog entries -- you write one for the whole
run, so the PR carries a single coherent entry instead of one file per agent.

The repo requires one entry per project the PR touches. Determine which
projects your integrated commits touched:

```bash
git diff --name-only "$MNGR_GIT_BASE_BRANCH"..HEAD | sed -n 's#^\(libs/[^/]*\|apps/[^/]*\)/.*#\1#p' | sort -u
```

A path outside `libs/` and `apps/` (e.g. `scripts/`, `.github/`) belongs to the
synthetic `dev` project, whose directory is `dev/`.

For each project, write `<project_dir>/changelog/<branch>.md`, where `<branch>`
is your branch name with slashes replaced by dashes. Describe the user-visible
changes that pertain to *that* project, drawing on the mapper summaries you
integrated. Group them by theme rather than listing one bullet per agent; a
reader wants to know what changed about the suite, not which agent did it.
Separate bullets with a blank line. Commit this as `[CHANGELOG]`.

If you integrated no code at all, still write an entry for the project whose
tests the run targeted, saying the run found no changes to integrate and
summarizing what was escalated.

# Open the pull request

Open the run's pull request yourself, so its description can carry the run's
findings. Do this even when you integrated nothing.

These environment variables are provided to you:

- `GH_TOKEN` -- token authorized to push and open a PR on this repo
- `TMR_GITHUB_REPOSITORY` -- `owner/repo`
- `TMR_BASE_BRANCH` -- the branch to target
- `TMR_RUN_URL` -- the CI run that launched this TMR run
- `TMR_PR_LABEL`, `TMR_PR_ASSIGNEES` -- may be empty; apply only if set

First make sure there is something to open a PR from. GitHub rejects a pull
request whose head and base are identical, so if you integrated no commits,
create an empty one:

```bash
BRANCH=$(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD)
if [ -z "$(git rev-list --max-count=1 "$TMR_BASE_BRANCH..$BRANCH")" ]; then
    git commit --allow-empty -m "[TMR] No changes to integrate from this run"
fi
git push "https://x-access-token:$GH_TOKEN@github.com/$TMR_GITHUB_REPOSITORY.git" "HEAD:refs/heads/$BRANCH"
```

Build the title and the findings section with the helper rather than by hand --
it reads the same outcome files and will not miscount:

```bash
INPUTS={{ inputs_dirname }}
TITLE=$(uv run --project libs/mngr_tmr python -m imbue.mngr_tmr.pr_summary --title "$BRANCH" "$INPUTS")
FINDINGS=$(uv run --project libs/mngr_tmr python -m imbue.mngr_tmr.pr_summary "$INPUTS")
```

Then open the PR as a draft, against `$TMR_BASE_BRANCH`, with that title and a
body containing, in order:

1. The mechanical provenance line: that this is an automated PR from TMR run
   `$TMR_RUN_URL`, followed by the report link:
{% if report_url %}   `HTML report: {{ report_url }} (also attached as the tmr-report artifact on the workflow run).`
{% else %}   `HTML report: attached as the tmr-report artifact on the workflow run; download and open index.html.`
{% endif %}
2. `$FINDINGS` verbatim -- the mapper status breakdown and escalations table.
3. A short prose paragraph of your own: the themes you saw across the run, what
   you normalized, and anything a reviewer should look at first. This is the one
   part that is yours to write; keep it to a few sentences.

Use the `gh` CLI if it is available (`gh pr create --draft --base ... --head ...
--title ... --body ...`, plus `--label`/`--assignee` when those variables are
set). If `gh` is not installed, POST to
`https://api.github.com/repos/$TMR_GITHUB_REPOSITORY/pulls` with
`Authorization: Bearer $GH_TOKEN` using python3's urllib, then apply any label
and assignees via the issues API.

Record the resulting PR URL in your outcome as `pull_request_url`. If opening
the PR fails, do not abort the run: record the failure in
`pull_request_error` and continue to publishing the outputs archive, so the
orchestrator still gets your results.

# Writing the outcome and publishing outputs

After cherry-picking, write the result atomically to avoid races with the
orchestrator reading it:

1. First write to .test_output/{{ reducer_outcome_filename }}.draft (relative to the git repo root)
2. Then rename (mv) the .draft file to .test_output/{{ reducer_outcome_filename }}

The schema is:

{"squashed_branches": ["branch1", "branch2"],
 "squashed_commit_hash": "abc1234",
 "impl_priority": ["branch3"],
 "impl_commit_hashes": {"branch3": "def5678"},
 "failed": ["branch4"],
 "normalizations": [{"summary_markdown": "Extracted the mngr-list agent-running check into e2e.assert_agent_running (verified across 6 tests)"}],
 "escalations": [{"kind": "BLOCKER", "title": "codex tests need OpenAI credentials", "detail_markdown": "test_create_codex mocks codex with sleep because OPENAI_API_KEY is absent from the test env; a real fake-codex fixture or credentials are needed."}],
 "pull_request_url": "https://github.com/owner/repo/pull/1234"}

Fields:
- squashed_branches: branch names whose test/doc commits were squashed
- squashed_commit_hash: commit hash of the squashed test/doc commit (short is fine)
- impl_priority: impl branch names in priority order, highest first
- impl_commit_hashes: mapping of impl branch name to its commit hash on the integrated branch
- failed: branch names that could not be integrated
- normalizations: suite-wide cleanups you applied and verified (each with summary_markdown). Omit or use [] if none.
- escalations: everything you could NOT resolve or verify, to surface to the user -- both your own findings and the unresolved ones carried through from the test agents. Each has kind ("BLOCKER" or "SHARED_PATTERN"), title, and detail_markdown. Omit or use [] if none.
- pull_request_url: URL of the pull request you opened.
- pull_request_error: present only if opening the PR failed; describe what went wrong.

Then, finally, publish the outputs archive. Run this from the git repo root:

{{ publish_snippet }}

This MUST be the very last step. The orchestrator polls for outputs.tar.gz
and treats its appearance as the signal that you are done. The .tmp + rename
sequence prevents the orchestrator from reading a half-written archive.

